2026-04-16 12:18:43 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module internal wiring between battery and output (polarity / short fault)'] hypothesis_explanation='The original battery was dead and has been replaced, but there is still essentially 0 V at the PSU output cables even though continuity from the battery to both output leads measures ~0 Ω. This implies that the battery positive and negative are effectively shorted together inside the power‑supply module (or otherwise miswired so that both external leads are at the same potential). The LED branch shows a plausible resistance (~1 kΩ) and is simply unpowered because the main rails are shorted or incorrectly tied, preventing any voltage from developing across the output or LED.\n\nGiven that the continuity test already verified low resistance from each battery terminal to its corresponding output lead, an additional unwanted connection (short) between the positive and negative rails within the PSU module is the most likely remaining fault. Repairing/replacing the PSU internal wiring (or the whole PSU module) to remove this internal short/miswiring should restore 12 V at the output cables, after which the rest of the chain can function.'
